jparsec.io

Class ReadFile

  • java.lang.Object
    • jparsec.io.ReadFile
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class ReadFile
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable
    A suitable class for reading files in the hard disk or located inside any of the .jar files of the dependencies, for instance orbital elements of comets and asteroids. Available formats are SkyMap and Minor Planet Center. When reading files with an instance of this class be aware that there's an internal restriction about the number of times a given file can be read and its data hold in different instances of this class. The maximum allowed times is internally set to 3, which means, for instance, that 3 is the maximum allowed number of different sky renderings that can be hold in memory per thread. This is obviously done to save memory. When changing the time in sky rendering many times, only the set of objects (orbital elements for comets and asteroids, list of stars, ...) corrsponding to the 3 most recent renderings are in memory using the DataBase class. This value (3) is the value of Configuration.MAX_CACHE_SIZE, and can be changed, but it is not recommended to increase it.

    NOTE: The availability of the SkyMap format is only for our practical purposes, since it is a popular commercial program used by astronomers. This does not mean any particular interest at all.

    Version:
    1.0
    Author:
    T. Alonso Albi - OAN (Spain)

      • readFileOfAsteroids

        public void readFileOfAsteroids()
                         throws JPARSECException
        Reads an example file with orbital elements of asteroids formatted in the standard way, established by the Minor Planet Center or either the commercial program SkyMap. The format is the same for trans-Neptunian or Centaur objects.

        An example of MPC format is: 

         00001    3.34  0.12 K0636 129.98342   73.23162   80.40970   10.58687  0.0800102  0.21432279   2.7653949    MPC 24219  4676  62 1839-1994 0.54 M-v 30  Bowell     0000             (1) Ceres

        An example of SkyMap format is: 

               1 Ceres                                  2005 08 18.0  86.9545  2.765979 0.080014  73.3924  80.4097  10.5860   3.34  0.12

        After the file is successfully read, the objects are stored using DataBase with the identifier returned by getDataBaseID().

        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If the reference time is invalid.

      • readFileOfComets

        public void readFileOfComets()
                      throws JPARSECException
        Reads an example file with orbital elements of comets formatted in the standard way, established by the Minor Planet Center or either the commercial program SkyMap.

        An example of MPC format is: 

         0002P         2007 04 19.3070  0.339201  0.847059  186.5211  334.5780   11.7556  20060922  11.5  6.0  2P/Encke

        An example of SkyMap format is: 

         2P Encke                                       2003 12 29.8945  0.338844       0.847212 186.5134 334.5891  11.7634  11.5   6.0

        After the file is successfully read, the objects are stored using DataBase with the identifier returned by getDataBaseID().

        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If the reference time is invalid.

      • readFileOfNEOs

        public void readFileOfNEOs(double jd,
                  double maxDays)
                    throws JPARSECException
        Reads the file of Near Earth Objects, with orbital elements formatted in the standard way, established by the Minor Planet Center,

        After the file is successfully read, the objects are stored using DataBase with the identifier returned by getDataBaseID().

        Parameters:
        jd - The date for the ephemerides calculations. Set to -1 to get all NEOS without limiting the date.
        maxDays - The maximum number of days for the elements validity. In case perihelion time is outside limit jd +/- maxDays, the NEO will not be returned. Recommended value is 365 days or lower.
        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If the reference time is invalid.

      • readFileOfOldComets

        public static java.util.ArrayList<OrbitalElement> readFileOfOldComets(AstroDate astro,
                                                      int years)
                                                               throws JPARSECException
        Reads a file with orbital elements of old comets.
        Parameters:
        astro - Optional date to retrieve only some of the comets around it. Can be null.
        years - Maximum number of years around the date to retrieve a given comet. Set to 10 to retrieve all comets with elements referred to a date within +/- 10 years from the input date.
        Returns:
        The list of elements, or null if none is found for the interval of years.
        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If the reference time is invalid.

      • readFileOfProbes

        public void readFileOfProbes()
                      throws JPARSECException
        Reads a file with orbital elements of probes in the JPARSEC format.

        An example of such format is: 

         Galileo-1       e 4.3224100 24.682800 -175.312000 0.8323240 1.2979700 0.19785000 -158.241000 11/09.0/1989   1950    0 0 1989 11 9.690 1990 02 10.26

        After the file is successfully read, the objects are stored using DataBase with the identifier returned by getDataBaseID().

        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If the reference time is invalid.

      • readFileOfAsteroidsFromExternalFile

        public void readFileOfAsteroidsFromExternalFile(java.lang.String[] file)
                                         throws JPARSECException
        Reads an external file with orbital elements of asteroids formatted in the standard way, established by the Minor Planet Center or either the commercial program SkyMap. The format is the same for trans-Neptunian or Centaur objects.

        An example of MPC format is: 

         00001    3.34  0.12 K0636 129.98342   73.23162   80.40970   10.58687  0.0800102  0.21432279   2.7653949    MPC 24219  4676  62 1839-1994 0.54 M-v 30  Bowell     0000             (1) Ceres

        An example of SkyMap format is: 

               1 Ceres                                  2005 08 18.0  86.9545  2.765979 0.080014  73.3924  80.4097  10.5860   3.34  0.12

        After the file is successfully read, the objects are stored using DataBase with the identifier returned by getDataBaseID().

        Parameters:
        file - The read file. If null the file will be read from pathToFile.
        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If the reference time is invalid.

      • readFileOfNaturalSatellites

        public void readFileOfNaturalSatellites(Target.TARGET planet)
                                 throws JPARSECException
        Reads a file with orbital elements of natural satellites formatted in a way defined by the JPL. See http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/?sat_elem for more information. Results are copied to DataBase.

        An example of such format is given next. Note the column positions are not taken into account, only the order where the elements are given and the overall format. See example files, named like JPL_natural_satellites.txt. 

         Mars
 Mean orbital elements referred to the local Laplace planes
 Epoch 1950 Jan. 1.00 TT
 Solution: MAR033
 Phobos 9380.  0.0151 150.247  92.474 1.075 164.931 1128.8444155  0.319  1.131  2.262 317.724 52.924 0.046 5
 Deimos 23460. 0.0002 290.496 296.230 1.793 339.600  285.1618919  1.262 26.892 54.536 316.700 53.564 0.897 5
        Parameters:
        planet - Planet whose satellites should be obtained.
        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If the read fails.
